li.p:
We will use the Pythagorean Theorem: x^2+h^2=16^2, first we length of the missing side x by plugging in h=12

x^2+12^2=16^2 \implies x^2=16^2-12^2 \implies x=\sqrt{16^2-12^2}=\sqrt{112}

Then we take the implicit time derivative

\frac{d}{dt}\left[x^2+h^2=16^2\right]


2x\frac{dx}{dt}+2h\frac{dh}{dt}=0

Finally substitute in what is known and solve for \displaystyle \frac{dx}{dt}

2(\sqrt{112})\frac{dx}{dt}+2(12)(-4)=0 \implies \frac{dx}{dt}=\frac{24}{\sqrt{112}}

Thus the base is moving away from the wall at a rate of \displaystyle \frac{dx}{dt}=\frac{24}{\sqrt{112}} feet per second.

We will use the Pythagorean Theorem: x^2+50^2=y^2. Note that now the y is the hypotenuse and it is varying!  First we length of the missing side x by plugging in y=12

x^2+50^2=130^2 \implies x^2=130^2-50^2 \implies x=\sqrt{130^2-50^2}=120

Then we take the implicit time derivative

\frac{d}{dt}\left[x^2+50^2=y^2\right]


2x\frac{dx}{dt}+0=2y\frac{dy}{dt}

Finally substitute in what is known and solve for \displaystyle \frac{dy}{dt}

2(120)(10)=2(130)\frac{dy}{dt} \implies \frac{dy}{dt}=\frac{120}{\sqrt{130}}

The distance from the person to the boat is increasing at a rate of \displaystyle \frac{dy}{dt}=\frac{12}{\sqrt{13}} feet per minute.

solution.p:
By the Pythagorean Theorem, we know that x^2 + 90^2 = z^2;
differentiating with respect to t, we have

  2x\frac{dx}{dt} = 2z\frac{dz}{dt}
.

We are given that at the instant x = 45, r = \frac{90}{8}=\frac{45}4,
so by Pythagoras, s = \frac{45}{4}\sqrt{17}.
In addition, at this same instant we know that
\left. \frac{dx}{dt} \right|_{x = 45} = 100 and \left. \frac{dr}{dt} \right|_{x = 45} = 30.
Applying this information, we end up with 

\left.\frac{ds}{dt}\right|_{x=45}=\mathstrut\amp\left.\left(\frac xs\frac{dx}{dt}+\frac rs\frac{dr}{dt}\right)\right|_{x=45}
=\mathstrut\amp\frac{45}{\big(\frac{45}4\sqrt{17}\big)}(100)+\frac{\big(\frac{45}4\big)}{\big(\frac{45}4\sqrt{17}\big)}(30)
=\mathstrut\amp\frac{400}{\sqrt{17}}+\frac{30}{\sqrt{17}}
=\mathstrut\amp\frac{430}{\sqrt{17}}
\approx\mathstrut\amp104.2903 \ \text{ft/sec}
.
Therefore, the distance between the ball and the runner is at this instant increasing 
at a rate of about 104.29 feet per second.
